<br>
Either solo or in a well balanced group. That is pretty much 99% of what I do. <br>
<br>
I have played both classes to high realm ranks and have a pretty good idea of their strengths and weaknesses. I wish I didn't have to spend too much time on this because it isn't really part of my original argument other than a simple side comment, but I guess I will go into it a bit.<br>
<br>
When I say survivability, I am not specifically speaking about pure defense. Minstrels might have an edge there, but not much of one if at all. Rather I am speaking about their status as a priority target because of SoS. Minstrels generally die quickly against good groups.<br>
================<br>
This contradicts your earlier comments that a skald was comparable damage to a warrior.<br>
<br>
Your contention seems to be that a skald has greater survivability because minst are a greater threat and therefore skalds survive longer because they aren't targeted to be killed.  Well, that's not how rvr works really.  it usually goes &quot;easy kill, important kill, tough  kill&quot; in that order.  Skald falls under easy kill.  Minst falls under important/tough, primarily because most classes can't get a grip on them once they have used their RAs or if they are under the influence of Mezz reduction/immunity timers.<br>
<br>
for the record i have a RR6l4 Skald and partial ownership of a rr8l2 minst.  So i've seen it from both sides and i can guarentee you my minst lives far longer then my skald 99% of the time, primarily because i can do my job without being right in the front line area, which is not feasible for a skald to be effective, they must wade in.  A minst can maintain a 1000 unit buffer to most of the dangerous combat while at the same time reducing the ranged threat to them while on the move (mezz and kite). Mezz may not stick after the inital cast, but it DOES interrupt, and thats all you need to survive a ranged caster and interrupt healers at a distance, just run around and spam cast it on them, you've done your entire team an invaluable service while maintaining a posture that allows you to live through most if not all fights.  To say the AE mezz is inconsequential is horribly inaccurate, a well played minst can lock down entire armies of ranged attackers with it and cause healers a constant headache.<br>
<br>
Skald has 1 timered range interrupt at 1500 units, other then that they have to close to a min. 700 to continue to interrupt casters, then its a timer.<br>
<br>
Minst are designed to be survivable support classes, tho it may be true that skalds and minst both die a lot in close combat with heavy tanks, a minst has the optiont to do his job without being in that situation where a skald doesn't.<br>
<br>
Your selective use of stun is your choice, however that doesn't mean that other uses for it don't make it a very powerful tool, for instance using Stun on Pbaer who is about to nail your CCed realmmates can save them a substantial amount of damage.  there are quite a fewer other uses for stun, to be honest, your better off using mezz on the move to stop most runners (except those with immunity) because then when you close to combat and engage, you can stun mid combat with no timer concern if the fight becomes too tough.<br>
================<br>
Regarding this comment <br>
&quot;he instant snare is by far the most useful of the CC options because it has range, interrupts and lasts a long time. Another understated benefit of the skald is his ability to use snare styles. The minstrel has one snare style and it is in a chain off of their no &quot;to hit&quot; detaunt in the thrust line. Most minstrels use blades in the first place. Skalds have access to reasonably accessible snare styles in every weapon line, especially Hammer. I use sword, but I still have access to a side style snare which I get off more than you might guess and the one off the assault chain, which I use a lot.&quot;<br>
<br>
====<br>
This would be true if the snare didn't break upon next damage to the target. very very rarely when you are chasing somebody through an active battle field will you land a snare that really sticks for more then a couple of seconds with the tons of AE being thrown around and people trying to take a shot at the target as its running past.  Additionally, bleed styles, dots and some pulsing effects can break snare.  Once you've snared and had it broken, you've given the target in question root immunity, which means should they get away from you (like say you get cced or otherwise stopped) the next caster they go after has no CC option to stop them unless they try to mezz (sm)<br>
<br>
From a skill set perspective, skald snare is incredibly inferior to prevent flight, both in its casted form and its styled form.<br>
<br>
This statement is also incorrect<br>
====<br>
Now, even if minstrels have an edge in the survivability line and you can argue that they are roughly equal in terms of CC, skalds make up for it with far superior damage. Minstrel damage even with higher weaponspec is mediocre at best. Skald melee damage is mediocre at worst and extremely good at best. You cannot find a minstrel that can take down a caster in one round of combat. You just can't do it.<br>
====<br>
<br>
A low stealth high weapon/instrument minst is very very capable of taking down people in 1 round of combat (casters)<br>
<br>
Minst and skald are on identical weaponskill tables, the myth that skalds have higher weaponskill was perpetuated by people comparing low str minst chars to Trolls skalds.  it's simply not true.<br>
<br>
A minst with an Anchor (slow 1 hand weapon) will do very good damage per strike vs cloth casters, add in their DDs and mastery of pain II (aug str one helps also) and they can approach close to 430 with an opening blow + 300 from DDs, that's enough to take out an unbuffed caster. Should they perfect crit on the attack or get a positional off, that damage goes up quite a bit.  Plus they can stun said caster and beat on them a couple more times with the positional of their choice without worrying about the first shot breaking their mezz and the caster qc ccing them or lifetapping them.<br>
<br>
Wish i had my other computer up, i'd throw up the screenie of minst hitting  mana eld for 419, 189 139 (dds) then hitting for 560.  The mana eld lived because he got an insta from his druid.  Clearly there is a crit in there (mana eld took shot), but the point is, minst can do = damage to skald if they low spec stealth, which they don't NEED in rvr.  Skald can only spec for max damage if they gimp their BS song a bit.<br>
<br>
<br>
======<br>
&quot;Skalds are very capable of this and in playing a Skald this ability has dramatically changed the way I played the game from someone blindly assisting to someone that can keep 2-3 targets occupied while taking down a healer or caster that is causing trouble''<br>
<br>
Refer to my comment about tying up everyone in the back areas with chain mezzes.  compare how many people a skald can tie up compared to a minst then.<br>
<br>
=====<br>
I dunno. I just find it funny when skalds complain about minstrels being so much better when I have dueled dozens and never had one take me below 50% life in a 1 vs 1 fight. And beyond that they really don't bring much more to a group than a Skald. I think damage add is more important than ablative chant when you factor BoF into the equation. Otherwise they are both things that really won't change the outcome of battles. Power song is in the same boat as Heal song. Neither are useful in combat. So really what it boils down to is this in terms of group benefits that actually affect the outcome of a battle:<br>
<br>
Skalds: Damage add, resists, instant medium duration CC<br>
<br>
Minstrels: Ablative chant, castable medium duration CC<br>
<br>
=====<br>
<br>
a minst + Pally interaction is greater then any duo in mid.<br>
<br>
IE a minst + pally = Damage add, AF buff, Ablative, heal + extras <br>
<br>
+ minst get insta Stun, castable AE mezz which interrupts.<br>
<br>
That's ignoring the SOS, BOF aspect entirely.  Granted Pally can't get ring of tears, but its a minor issue<br>
<br>
skald has no favorable duo in mid...cept maybe the RM but thats questionable.<br>
<br>
You must balance classes around how they interact with other classes in their own realm otherwise you can't balance ever.  To see the extremes of why ignoring class duo/group combinations, look at the dreds and see what happens when you put a necro + animist in a keep situation.  Sure, solo they may not make a vastly overpowered combination, but combined, they can defeat Dozens.<br>
<br>
How does that apply to your comment you ask?  you are taking it as a 1 v 1 and you beat minst.  well for starters, you never know what the other guys spec is, he could be 50 inst/50 stealth for all you know, its not a controlled thing.  but you expand it to a group setting and suddenly the minst increases in power exponetially while a skald has exactly the same benefits solo, in a group or in an army.  Additionally, you are comparing a class to class where you put a minst specifically in their worst element, that is close combat 1 v 1 vs a skalds strongest case, 1 v 1.  you allow that minst to kite and start the combat from range, suddenly things change. it becomes an entirely different battle.<br>
